[{"id":"use-as-a-library-npm-0#0","metadata":{"content":"The embeddable host — what the gateway itself builds on — ships as [`@rckflr/mcpwasm`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@rckflr/mcpwasm):","okf_concept":"use-as-a-library-npm-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"Use as a library (npm)"}},{"id":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-4#0","metadata":{"content":"Pointing the runtime at a raw GitHub URL does **not** work: `new URL(...).origin` keeps only scheme+host+port, so `https://raw.githubusercontent.com/you/repo/main/` collapses to `https://raw.githubusercontent.com` — the `you/repo/main` part (and therefore `/llms.txt`) is gone. `--serve` is the practical alternative: it starts an internal static file server (bound to `127.0.0.1` only, never exposed","okf_concept":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-4","okf_type":"docs","title":"Local MCP runtime — no gateway at all"}},{"id":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-1#0","metadata":{"content":"MCP client configuration (Claude Code, Cursor, …):","okf_concept":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"Local MCP runtime — no gateway at all"}},{"id":"static-mcp-vs-a-traditional-mcp-server-2#0","metadata":{"content":"The takeaway that doesn't fit in a table: a traditional MCP server answers \"how do I expose this logic as a tool?\" Static MCP additionally answers \"how do I run code from an origin I don't fully trust?\" If you write and control the server yourself, traditional is simpler and none of this is necessary. Static MCP matters when the tool code comes from *someone else*, and you want a verifiable guaran","okf_concept":"static-mcp-vs-a-traditional-mcp-server-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"Static MCP vs. a traditional MCP server"}},{"id":"why-1#0","metadata":{"content":"mcpwasm removes the trust requirement for the *code*:","okf_concept":"why-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"Why"}},{"id":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-3#0","metadata":{"content":"#### Developing your own skills: `--serve <dir>`","okf_concept":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-3","okf_type":"docs","title":"Local MCP runtime — no gateway at all"}},{"id":"why-2#0","metadata":{"content":"- The tool runs in a separate QuickJS-wasm context with no host globals beyond what the host predefines (`registerTool`, `host`). No `fetch`, no `process`, no disk, no secrets. - The platform secret (e.g. a Stripe key) stays on the host side. The tool can only ask the host to perform a *named* internal action via `host.callInternal` (sync host) or a scoped `host.fetchOrigin` (async host). The host","okf_concept":"why-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"Why"}},{"id":"static-mcp-vs-a-traditional-mcp-server-0#0","metadata":{"content":"In mcpwasm, *publishing* (static files + a hash) and *execution* (a runtime that discovers, verifies, and sandboxes on demand) are two separate things. In a traditional MCP server they are the same thing — the server you deploy *is* the execution, with no isolation layer in between.","okf_concept":"static-mcp-vs-a-traditional-mcp-server-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"Static MCP vs. a traditional MCP server"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-4#0","metadata":{"content":"This repo integrates with the [llms-txt-skills](https://github.com/MauricioPerera/llms-txt-skills) standard via two provisional extensions adopted in the spec: **executable skills** (v0.4, with *origin memory*) and **skill attestations** (v0.2). See the dedicated sections below.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-4","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-5#0","metadata":{"content":"```bash npx -y @rckflr/mcpwasm --serve ./my-skills-repo","okf_concept":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-5","okf_type":"docs","title":"Local MCP runtime — no gateway at all"}},{"id":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-0#0","metadata":{"content":"The package also ships a stdio MCP server that runs an origin's skills **locally**: it fetches `/llms.txt`, verifies every `tool_sha256`, loads each verified skill into its own QuickJS-wasm context, and speaks MCP over stdin/stdout — so a static site (e.g. a GitHub Pages *user* site) becomes an MCP server on your machine with zero deployed infrastructure on either side:","okf_concept":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"Local MCP runtime — no gateway at all"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-0#0","metadata":{"content":"[![CI](https://github.com/MauricioPerera/mcpwasm/actions/workflows/ci.yml/badge.svg)](https://github.com/MauricioPerera/mcpwasm/actions/workflows/ci.yml) [![npm](https://img.shields.io/npm/v/%40rckflr%2Fmcpwasm)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@rckflr/mcpwasm)","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"use-as-a-library-npm-1#0","metadata":{"content":"- In Cloudflare Workers, pass a pre-built asyncify module via the `quickjs` option (see `worker-gateway.mjs` for the `CompiledWasm` import pattern and import `@rckflr/mcpwasm/shim` first). - Subpath exports: `/host` (sync `ToolHost`), `/host-async`, `/mcp-core`, `/mcp-core-async`, `/llmstxt-parse`, `/shim`. - The sync `ToolHost` lazy-imports the optional peer `quickjs-emscripten` unless you pass a","okf_concept":"use-as-a-library-npm-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"Use as a library (npm)"}},{"id":"why-0#0","metadata":{"content":"MCP clients (Claude, Cursor, others) can call arbitrary tools. Running a third-party tool's code directly in your backend means that code can read your secrets, hit your DB, phone home, or loop forever. You either trust the author fully or you don't run the tool.","okf_concept":"why-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"Why"}},{"id":"static-mcp-vs-a-traditional-mcp-server-1#0","metadata":{"content":"| | Static MCP — local (`npx @rckflr/mcpwasm`) | Static MCP — gateway | Traditional MCP server | |---|---|---|---| | What the publisher ships | Static files: `llms.txt` + `tool.js` (+ `SKILL.md`) | Same static files | A running server process (any language) | | Infrastructure the publisher operates | None — GitHub Pages, R2, any static host | None — same | The whole server: uptime, scaling, patchi","okf_concept":"static-mcp-vs-a-traditional-mcp-server-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"Static MCP vs. a traditional MCP server"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-2#0","metadata":{"content":"mcpwasm is the reference implementation: a sandboxed runtime for third-party MCP tools (untrusted tool code inside QuickJS-wasm on Cloudflare Workers), plus a gateway that turns any static site publishing `llms.txt` with executable skills into an MCP server.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-1#0","metadata":{"content":"**Static MCP: your tools are files, not servers.** Tools are published as static, hash-verified content and executed sandboxed on demand. What static site hosting did to web servers — \"don't run Apache, publish HTML\" — this does to MCP servers: don't run an MCP server, publish files. The publisher needs zero infrastructure; the MCP server is materialized per request from those files and evaporates","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-2#0","metadata":{"content":"Honest v1 limits (stated in `bin/mcpwasm-local.mjs`): no origin memory (`host.memorySearch` is absent; skills that call it fail controlled, which the spec allows), no attestation verification (locally, trust is your choice of origin — hash verification remains mandatory), and discovery runs once per process (restart to refresh). Hash verification and the sandbox model (per-skill contexts, origin-s","okf_concept":"local-mcp-runtime-no-gateway-at-all-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"Local MCP runtime — no gateway at all"}},{"id":"npx-y-rckflr-mcpwasm-serve-my-skills-rep-0#0","metadata":{"content":"This is meant for developing and testing your own skills locally before publishing them (to GitHub Pages or any other static host) — not for browsing someone else's GitHub repo directly. Path-traversal requests against the internal file server are rejected (resolved and checked against the served directory's root); covered by `npm run local`.","okf_concept":"npx-y-rckflr-mcpwasm-serve-my-skills-rep-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"npx -y @rckflr/mcpwasm --serve ./my-skills-repo --port 4000   (fixed port, optional)"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-3#0","metadata":{"content":"Think \"php-wasm, but for MCP tools\": the platform owner embeds the host, loads `tool.js` files, and each tool runs isolated in a QuickJS WebAssembly sandbox. The only bridge from the sandbox to the platform's internals is an explicit capability the host injects. No capability, no access.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-3","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm — Static MCP"}}]